    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Prison and Mental Illness</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gennifer Furst letter on Sept 6 article hails Ithaca, NY, police effort to prevent killings by the mentally ill</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Trying to Prevent the Next Killer Rampage'' (front page, Sept. 6):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Trying to Prevent the Next Killer Rampage'' (front page, Sept. 6):</p>
        <p>The ''problem-solving'' approach that the Ithaca, N.Y., police department takes in dealing with the mentally ill is commendable. Without its services, these people would likely end up behind bars.</p>
        <p>Imprisoning the mentally ill after a tragedy has already occurred, rather than providing them with preventive mental health care services,  is an expensive and inhumane policy. We cannot continue to dump the mentally ill into prisons. This country has the largest prison population in the world; when is the last time anyone was cured by spending time in jail?</p>
        <p>GENNIFER FURST  New York, Sept. 8, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is project associate, Prison Visiting Project, Correctional Association of New York.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
